# Tool I/O Contracts: Typed Inputs & Outputs for Every Tool

Every tool in the system MUST have a typed I/O contract that declares what it accepts and what it produces. This contract is registered in the Action I/O Registry so that skills, composed workflows, the Agent Factory Workflow Composer, and other tools can discover and validate tool wiring programmatically.

## Why This Matters

Without typed contracts:
- The Workflow Composer can't show what a tool produces for downstream wiring
- Skills can't validate that their tool sequences are type-compatible
- Composed workflows break silently when a tool's output shape changes
- Agent Factory playbooks can't link step inputs to upstream outputs
- There is no machine-readable documentation of what a tool does

---

## The Type System

### Core Types

A small, pragmatic type system. These are the ONLY types used in I/O contracts:

| Type | Python | Examples | Notes |
|------|--------|----------|-------|
| `text` | `str` | Free text, IDs, names, content, markdown | **The universal connector** — everything coerces to text |
| `number` | `int \| float` | Counts, scores, amounts, indices | |
| `boolean` | `bool` | Success flags, feature toggles | |
| `date` | `str` (ISO 8601) | `"2026-02-14"`, `"2026-02-14T17:00:00Z"` | Stored as text, semantically a date |
| `record` | `Dict[str, Any]` | Structured objects with named fields | Fields are individually addressable |
| `list[T]` | `List[T]` | Arrays of items where T is any core type | |
| `file_ref` | `Dict` | `{document_id, title, file_type, folder_path, scope}` | Standardized document reference |
| `any` | `Any` | Accepts anything | Escape hatch — use sparingly |

### `text` Is the Universal Type

**`text` is the lingua franca.** Most tool inputs accept `text`. Most tool outputs include `text` fields. Free text is always a valid type.

This is by design:
- LLM task steps produce `text` as their primary output
- Users type `text` into the chat
- Document content is `text`
- Entity names, queries, file paths — all `text`

When in doubt about an input type, use `text`. It is always valid.

### Automatic Coercion Rules

The type system is **permissive by default**. When an output of type A is wired to an input of type B, coercion happens automatically:

#### Always Allowed (lossless, silent):

```
number   → text       "42"
boolean  → text       "true" / "false"
date     → text       "2026-02-14T17:00:00Z"
file_ref → text       document_id string
record   → text       JSON serialization
list[T]  → text       JSON serialization
any      → text       str() conversion
file_ref → record     Full metadata dict
number   → any        Always allowed
text     → any        Always allowed
(anything) → any      Always allowed
```

#### Allowed with Parsing (auto-attempted, warn on failure):

```
text     → number     Parse "42" → 42, "3.14" → 3.14
text     → boolean    "true"/"yes"/"1" → True, "false"/"no"/"0" → False
text     → date       ISO 8601 parse
text     → record     JSON parse
text     → list[T]    JSON parse (if array), or wrap as single-element list
text     → file_ref   Treat as document_id, resolve metadata
number   → boolean    0 → False, nonzero → True
```

#### Structural Coercion (collections):

```
list[record] → list[text]         Coerce each element
record.field → type_of_field      Field access (e.g., result.count → number)
list[record].field → list[T]      Array projection (e.g., results.title → list[text])
list[T][0] → T                    Index access
list[T].length → number           Length
```

#### Blocked (Workflow Composer shows error):

```
list     → number     Not meaningful
record   → number     Not meaningful
record   → boolean    Not meaningful
list     → boolean    Not meaningful (use list.length > 0 instead)
```

### Design Principles

1. **Never block a valid chain.** If a human would think "of course that should work," the type system should allow it.
2. **Coerce silently when lossless.** `number` → `text` just works, no warnings.
3. **Coerce with warning when lossy.** `text` → `number` attempts parsing, warns if it fails at runtime.
4. **Block only when truly nonsensical.** `list` → `boolean` is almost certainly a mistake.
5. **`text` connects everything.** Any output can become `text`. Any `text` input can receive anything.

