## Input Design Guidelines

### Prefer `text` for IDs and References

```python
# ❌ WRONG: Requires exact model — blocks valid upstream connections
class MyInputs(BaseModel):
    document: DocumentRef          # Upstream MUST produce a full DocumentRef

# ✅ CORRECT: Accepts any text — a document_id string from any source
class MyInputs(BaseModel):
    document_id: str = Field(description="Document ID")  # text type
```

### Use `text` for Free-Form Content

```python
# Many tools accept free text — this is fine and expected
class SummarizeInputs(BaseModel):
    content: str = Field(description="Text to summarize")  # text type
    # Could come from: read_file.content, crawl_url.content, llm_task output, etc.
```

### Use Specific Types Only When Semantically Meaningful

```python
class FilterInputs(BaseModel):
    items: List[dict] = Field(description="Items to filter")  # list[record]
    min_score: float = Field(description="Minimum score threshold")  # number
    # min_score SHOULD be number — "high" is not a valid threshold
```

### Accept `text` Even for Typed Fields (via Coercion)

If a tool input is `number`, the Workflow Composer allows wiring a `text` output to it — the runtime will parse. Don't add redundant `str` alternatives:

```python
# ❌ WRONG: Dual inputs for the same concept
class MyInputs(BaseModel):
    limit: int               # Number
    limit_str: str            # "Just in case it's a string"

# ✅ CORRECT: Single typed input — coercion handles text→number
class MyInputs(BaseModel):
    limit: int = Field(default=10, description="Max results")
    # If upstream sends "20" as text, runtime coerces to 20
```

